ROMS data extraction¶

roms.His and roms.Grid (roms.MHis and roms.MGrid for nesting configurations)¶

  • roms.His can be used to load his/avg/rst/clm files

  • It accepts the grid file as second argument if grid variables are not included in the main file.

  • roms.His.grid stores the grid object which can also be loaded with roms.Grid.

  • For nested applications there is also roms.MHis and roms.MGrid

In [1]:
import pylab as pl
import numpy as np

f='http://centolo.co.ieo.es:8080/thredds/dodsC/flor/test/avg_flor_1.nc4'
from okean import roms
r=roms.His(f)

domain resolution¶

In [4]:
x,y,dx,dy=g.resolution()

pl.figure(figsize=(6,2.7))
ax0=pl.axes((0.1,0.2,0.35,0.8))
ax1=pl.axes((0.6,0.2,0.35,0.8))
cbar=pl.axes((0.25,0.02,0.5,0.04))

# finding nice contour values:
from okean import ticks
vals=ticks.loose_label(np.ma.min((dx,dy)),np.ma.max((dx,dy)),10)

ax0.contourf(x,y,dx,vals)
h=ax1.contourf(x,y,dy,vals)
pl.colorbar(h,cax=cbar,orientation='horizontal')
[a.axis('equal') for a in (ax0,ax1)];

ax0.text(0.8,0.1,'$\Delta x$',transform=ax0.transAxes,fontsize=15)
ax1.text(0.8,0.1,'$\Delta y$',transform=ax1.transAxes,fontsize=15);

# play with projections and vis module:
fig,ax=pl.subplots(1,2)
pl.subplots_adjust(wspace=0.3)

# default data projection:
from okean import vis
d=vis.Data(xb0,yb0)
d.plot(ax=ax[0],proj=1,plot__zorder=1e3)

# default grid projection:
d.set_projection(g.proj_info['basemap_opts'])
d.plot(ax=ax[1],proj=1,plot__zorder=1e3)

# add some new data:
xb,yb=d.map(*r.grid.border(margin=10))
ax[1].plot(xb,yb)
j,i=20,20
x,y=d.map(r.grid.lon[j//2::j,i//2::i],r.grid.lat[j//2::j,i//2::i])
ax[1].plot(x,y,'bo',alpha=.3);

roms.His¶

slice k¶

slice along s-level

In [8]:
o=r.slicek('temp',-1,-1)
o.plot(clim=(27,30))
In [9]:
o=r.slicek('zeta',-1,-1)
o.plot(field__plot='contour')

Returned object can be used to plot directly (without using the vis module), with several options.

Or you can use the data stored in the object:

In [10]:
pl.contourf(o.x,o.y,o.v)
pl.colorbar()
   
pl.axis('equal')
d=0.15
pl.axis([xb0.min()-d,xb0.max()+d,yb0.min()-d,yb0.max()+d]);

All extras in the plot (usually the bottom) are stored in the extra attribute. All extras can also be plotted alone, e.g.:

In [11]:
o.extra[0].plot(cvals=range(20,100,10),field__cmap=pl.cm.plasma_r)

slice iso¶

iso surfaces can be calculated using fixed or variable iso value

  • using fixed iso:
In [12]:
o=r.sliceiso('temp',28,-1)
o.plot()
  • using variable value iso, e.g. the surface temp -1℃
In [13]:
sst=r.slicek('temp',-1,-1).v
o=r.sliceiso('temp',sst-1,-1)
o.plot()

slice z¶

slice at z-const, can use a fixed or variable depths:

  • using fixed depth:
In [14]:
o=r.slicez('salt',-40,-1)
o.plot()
  • using variable depths, e.g. the middle of the water column:
In [15]:
o=r.slicez('temp',-r.grid.h/2,-1)
o.plot()

slicez interpolates in the vertical linearly or using splines (default):

In [16]:
o0=r.slicez('temp',-40,-1)
o1=r.slicez('temp',-40,-1,spline=False)

pl.figure(figsize=(9,2.5))
ax,cax=[],[]
x0=0
for i in range(3):
    x0=x0+1/3.
    pos=x0+0.1,0.2,0.2,0.8
    cpos=pos[0]+pos[2]+0.003,pos[1],0.015,pos[3]
    ax+=[pl.axes(pos)]
    cax+=[pl.axes(cpos)]
         

o0.plot(ax=ax[0],cbax=cax[0],labels=False)
o1.plot(ax=ax[1],cbax=cax[1])

o2=vis.Data(o0.x,o0.y,o1.v-o0.v)
o2.copy_projection(o0)
o2.plot(ax=ax[2],cbax=cax[2],cmap='seismic',clim=(-0.15,0.15))
o2.draw_label('title','linear vs spline')

What if depth is very low, inside the tidal range, for instance. In such case, the option surf_mask may be used to repeat or not the data of the last s-level:

In [17]:
o0=r.slicez('salt',-0.9,-1)
o1=r.slicez('salt',-0.9,-1,surf_mask=False)

pl.figure(figsize=(6,2.7))
ax0=pl.axes((0.1,0.2,0.35,0.8))
ax1=pl.axes((0.6,0.2,0.35,0.8))

cbax0=pl.axes((0.46,0.2,0.02,0.8))
cbax1=pl.axes((0.96,0.2,0.02,0.8))

o0.plot(ax=ax0,cbax=cbax0)
o1.plot(ax=ax1,cbax=cbax1)

slice ll¶

slice along lon x lat path

In [19]:
import numpy as np
y0,x0=-27.5,-48.9
y1,x1=-27.5, -47.5
x=np.linspace(x0,x1,50)
y=np.linspace(y0,y1,50)

if 0:
    x2=-48
    y2=-26.8
    xx=np.linspace(x1,x2,50)
    yy=np.linspace(y1,y2,50)
    x=np.hstack((x,xx))
    y=np.hstack((y,yy))

xc=-48.3+0.35*np.cos(np.linspace(np.pi/3,2.1*np.pi,100))
yc=-28+0.35*np.sin(np.linspace(np.pi/3,2.1*np.pi,100))

q=r.grid.plot()
xm,ym=q.map(x,y)
q.ax.plot(xm,ym,'r',zorder=1e3);

xcm,ycm=q.map(xc,yc)
q.ax.plot(xcm,ycm,'r',zorder=1e3);

time series¶

time_series method can be used to extract time series at some depth or s-level and at all s-levels. It can also be used to extract vertical profiles

  • at all s-levels:
In [24]:
o=r.time_series('salt',-48,-27.5)
o.plot(figsize=(5,3),field__plot='contourf')

# adjust xticks:
mdates=pl.matplotlib.dates
loc = mdates.WeekdayLocator(byweekday=mdates.MO)
o.ax.xaxis.set_major_locator(loc)
o.ax.xaxis.set_major_formatter(mdates.DateFormatter('%d-%b'))
  • at fixed depth or s-level:
In [25]:
o=r.time_series('salt',-48,-27.5,depth=-40)
o1=r.time_series('salt',-48,-27.5,depth=-40,spline=False)
o2=r.time_series('salt',-48,-27.5,depth=20) # s-level

o.plot(figsize=(5,3))
o.ax.plot(o1.t,o1.v,'--')
o.ax.plot(o2.t,o2.v)
# or:
# o.extra+=[o1,o2]
# o.plot()

o.ax.xaxis.set_major_locator(loc)
o.ax.xaxis.set_major_formatter(mdates.DateFormatter('%d-%b'))
  • variable without depth dimension:
In [26]:
o=r.time_series('zeta',-48,-27.5)
o.plot(figsize=(5,3),d1__plot='fill_between')

# rotate xticks
for label in o.ax.get_xticklabels(which='major'):
    label.set_ha('right')
    label.set_rotation(30)
  • variable without time and depth dimensions:
In [27]:
o=r.time_series('h',-48,-27.5)
print('nearest longitude = %.4f'%o.x)
print('nearest latitude  = %.4f'%o.y)
print('depth = %.4f m'%o.v)

nearest longitude = -47.9976
nearest latitude  = -27.5037
depth = 71.3670 m
  • vertical profiles:
In [28]:
o=r.time_series('temp',-48,-27.5,times=0)
o.plot(figsize=(4,4))

pl.plot(np.zeros(sw.shape[0]),sw[:,0],'ro',ms=2)
pl.plot(np.zeros(sr.shape[0]),sr[:,0],'b+',ms=2);

it is still possible to plot each domain individually:

In [34]:
pl.figure(figsize=(7,2.7))
ax0=pl.axes((0.1,0.2,0.35,0.8))
ax1=pl.axes((0.6,0.2,0.35,0.8))

cbax0=pl.axes((0.46,0.2,0.02,0.8))
cbax1=pl.axes((0.96,0.2,0.02,0.8))

# during the previous o.plot a projection was set for all o elements
# need to remove them to have new projections for each domain
o[1].rm_projection()
o[2].rm_projection()

o[1].plot(ax=ax0,cbax=cbax0,extras=0)
o[2].plot(ax=ax1,cbax=cbax1,extras=0)
